2011-06-08T08:46:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-08/baotou-steel-dongfeng-auto-saic-vanke-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 6 points, or 0.2 percent, to
2,750.29. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  added 0.2 percent to 3,004.2.  Banks: Industrial and Commercial Bank of China Ltd. (601398
CH), the world’s largest bank by market value, lost 0.2 percent
to 4.42 yuan.  China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (601939 CH)
retreated 0.4 percent to 4.93 yuan. China should raise  interest
rates  as people are unwilling to save their money at banks at
current deposit rates, the National Business Daily reported
today, citing Chen Daofu, a researcher with the State Council’s
Development Research Center.  China Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (601600 CH), the
nation’s largest producer of the metal, surged by the 10 percent
daily limit to 11.14 yuan, its biggest gain since Sept. 28. The
company’s parent, Aluminum Corp. of China, has established a
unit from the consolidation of five rare-earth companies in
Jiangsu Province. The unit will have more than 30,000 metric
tons of rare-earth production capacity, according to an e-mailed
statement today.  China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), the country’s biggest
developer by market value, gained 3.7 percent to 8.10 yuan, the
most since Feb. 14. The company said sales in May rose 76.4
percent from a year ago to 9 billion yuan ($1.39 billion).  --Irene Shen, Bonnie Cao. Editor:  Matthew Oakley   To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
